occurrences.line_text: And the mad steele about doth fiercely fly,
About some carcase by the common way,
Her father and her friends about her lying,
The hue and cry was raysed all about;
So many theeues about him swarming are,
Their thickest troups, & round about him scattreth wide.
That fomed all about his bloody iawes.
Out of their townes did round about him throng,
The which his naked sides he wrapt abouts;
Out of his quiet slomber him abrade,
And now by this, Sir Satyrane abraid,
But when as I did out of sleepe abray,
For feare least her vnwares she should abrayd,
At last with irkesome trouble she abrayd;
So oftentimes he out of sleepe abrayd,
Which when as Scudamour, who now abrayd,
Thy dayes abridge, through proofe of puissance,
Their days mote be abridged through their corage stout.
And his abridged dayes in dolour wast,
That she desyrd th'abridgement of her fate,
Of straunge aduentures, which abroad did pas.
Their armes abroad, with gray mosse ouercast,
Which he had got abroad by purchase criminall.
He had in armes abroad wonne muchell fame,
And far abroad for straunge aduentures sought:
To weet of newes, that did abroad betide,
Or heard abroad of that her champion trew,
And wants supplide. And then againe abroad
And famous far abroad for warlike gest,
Abroad in armes, at home in studious kind
But that lame Hag, still as abroad he strew
Abroad thy fresh youthes fairest flowre, but lose
Speed thee to spred abroad thy beames bright?
Then in the countrey she abroad him sought,
That raungd abroad to seeke aduentures wilde,
To wander through the world abroad at will,
And yet three yeares I now abroad haue strayd,
With shrilling shriekes, Proteus abroad did roue,
And far abroad his mighty branches threw,
Flew first abroad, and all mens eares possest,
Did spred abroad, and throw in th'open wynd.
One day as he did raunge the fields abroad,
From seeking praise, and deeds of armes abrode,
And their true loues without suspition tell abrode.
Gan first inquire of tydings farre abrode;
Which after rest they seeking far abrode,
And gan to treate of deeds of armes abrode,
His weapons, which lay scattered all abrode,
So many learned impes, that shoote abrode,
But walkt abrode, and round about did rome,
Your owne dead Ladies head, to tell abrode your shame.
I heard report that farre abrode did fly,
Of things abrode, as next to hand did light,
To saue themselues, and scattered were abrode:
That they mote treat of things abrode at leasure;
Vpon a day he cast abrode to wend,
And wend abrode, though feeble and forlorne,
The trustie damzell bearing it abrode
Succeding There abruptly it did end,
Whose too long absence him had sore annoyd,
During his absence left in heauy care,
To which whiles absent he his mind did set,
Out of his sight her selfe once to absent.
Ne thence the Irishe Riuers absent were:
Ne any Knight was absent, that braue courage bore.
To his owne absent loue to be vntrew:
From teares abstaine, for griefe his hart did grate,
They gan abstaine from dint of direfull stroke,
And learne from pleasures poyson to abstaine:
Happy, who can abstaine, when Rancour rife
And counseld him abstaine from perilous fight:
Dernely vnto her called to abstaine,
Why doth mine hand from thine auenge abstaine,
Abstaine from pleasure, and restraine your will,
Stay stay, Sir Knight, for loue of God abstaine,
But being checkt, he did abstaine streight way,
Nathelesse so sore abuff to him it lent,
Would quite haue burst through great abundance of her smart.
For some, that hath abundance at his will,
To count the seas abundant progeny,
Of which he had with him abundant store,
The auncient Abus, where with courage stout
His sence abusd, and made him to misdeeme
Guyon by Archimage abusd,
Abusd her plenty, and fat swolne encreace
Which euer after they abusd to ill,
How to auenge himselfe so sore abusd,
For fault of few that haue abusd the same.
With such smooth termes her error I abusd,
The virgin, whom he had abusde so sore:
Had him abusde, and shamed yesterday;
So lewdly had abusde, as ye did lately heare.
Abusde, against all reason and all law,
And with false shewes abuse his fantasy,
So euery good to bad he doth abuse:
With whom in all abuse thou hast thy selfe defilde?
Or euer gentle Damzell so abuse:
O wretched man, that would abuse so gentle Dame.
For suffering such abuse, as knighhood shamed,
With such vaine shewes thy worldlings vile abuse:
If ought amis her liking may abuse:
As ignoraunt of seruants bad abuse,
And to thy will abuse? Thou walkest free,
To sell her borrowed beautie to abuse.
Her nature is all goodnesse to abuse,
Vnto abuse of lawlesse lust was lent,
But that she it with foule abuse did marre;
Her tyreling iade, was bent her to abuse;
And could no lenger beare so great abuse,
He from you take that chiefedome, which ye doe abuse.
And with her gealous termes his open eares abused.
And driue me to withdraw my blind abused loue.
And how that Hag his loue abused had
He them abused, through his subtill slights,
In vaine complayning, to be so abused.
As in despight to be so fowle abused
Whom he had feignd th'abuser of my loue to bee.
He would auenge th'abuses of that proud
Through fine abusion of that Briton mayd:
And foule abusion both his honour blent,
Foolish delights and fond abusions,
That direfull stroke thou dearely shalt aby.
But nought that wanteth rest, can long aby.
Yet thou false Squire his fault shalt deare aby,
To haue him slaine, or dearely doen aby.
Abett, perhaps he mote it deare aby.
Ne time would giue, nor any termes aby,
But th'vtmost end perforce for to aby,
Or deare aby, for why his Lord of old
It dearely shall aby, and death for handsell pay.
And late repentance, which shall long abyde.
With sacred rites and vowes for euer to abyde.
Else be ye sure he dearely shall abyde,
Did breake the launce, and let the head abyde:
In which full many louely Nymphes abyde,
To be the same, for whom they did abyde.
But like a bulwarke, firmely did abyde;
But Calidore did with her there abyde
Durst not the furie of his force abyde,
The which doth litle craue contented to abyde.
Who dyes the vtmost dolour doth abye,
The Gods doe dread, he dearely shall abye:
In th'huge abysse of his engulfing graue,
Downe in the bottome of the deepe Abysse,
And with her dolefull accent beare with him apart.
And to the waters fall tuning their accents fit.
Well to accept, and euermore embrace
Wherewith you to reward? Accept therefore
Did well accept, as well it did behoue,
But to accept her to his wedded wife.
It gladly did accept, as he did say.
She gladly did of that same babe accept,
Which he accepting well, as he could weete,
Which she accepting, he so neare her drew,
All which accepting, and with faithfull oth
Which she accepts, with thankes, and goodly gree,
That none mote haue accesse, nor inward fare,
By other accident that earst befell,
Or other accident, which him aghast;
By what straunge accident faire Chrysogone
And by what accident she there arriued:
For maruell of that accident extreame;
Which sodaine accident him much dismaid,
Of all the accident, there hapned plaine,
To be disordred by some accident:
There chaunst to them a dangerous accident;
This fatall chaunce, this dolefull accident,
To commun accidents still open layd,
And times comparing with their accidents,
And with vncomely weedes the gentle waue accloyes.
Whether high towring, or accoasting low,
Yet on his way, of none accompanide;
With whom as they thus rode accompanide,
So as he rode with them accompanide,
Saue that she algates him a while accompanide.
She might in equall armes accompany,
Him als accompanyd vpon the way
With whom as once I rode accompanyde,
Accompanyde with PhÃ¦dria the faire,
The marriage to accomplish vowd betwixt you twain.
They should accomplish both a knightly deed,
By which he mote accomplish his request,
Accomplished, that many deare complaind:
Tho when the terme is full accomplishid,
And high accompt throughout all Elfin land,
Causde me be called to accompt therefore,
How euer now accompted Elfins sonne,
That she in tract of time accompted was his owne.
Yet were not better, faire it to accord,
So happy peace they made and faire accord:
Accord of friends, consent of parents sought,
Which to them opened of his owne accord,
Forth passed on their way in faire accord,
Receiued is to grace and new accord,
In which accord the Prince was also plaste,
To plant or prune: for of their owne accord
To thinke, how causelesse of her owne accord
With perfect peace, and bandes of fresh accord,
Fell softly forth, as of his owne accord,
So did they all their former strife accord;
And to accord them all, this meanes deuiz'd:
She came of her accord, in spight of all his fone.
Till they with mariage meet might finish that accord.
An happie life with grace and good accord,
All which long sundred, doe at last accord
Certes your strife were easie to accord,
But to her yeelded of his owne accord;
Yet would she not thereto yeeld free accord,
But this proude Dame disdayning all accord,
Entyced her, to him for to accord.
All this accord, to which he Crudor had compeld.
Her selfe acknowledg'd bound for that accord,
Who ioyning ioy with her in one accord,
But the third time shall faire accordaunce make:
To faire accordaunce, and both faults to shade,
Then when they were accorded from the fray,
They are accorded: Agape
So well accorded forth they rode together
Thus when they all accorded goodly were,
Is now so well accorded all anew;
To shew it to this knight, according his desire.
Discourst his voyage long, according his request.
T'adorne thy forme according thy desart,
And others it to vse according to his kind.
Therefore a Fay he her according hight,
All shap't according their conditions,
According to their mindes like monstruous.
According to their kindes. Long worke it were,
Of this and that, according to each wit:
Them found all three according to their kynd:
But when as nought according to his mind
To which when he according did repaire,
Though I them all according their degree,
According their degrees disposed well.
According to the line of conscience,
According to the custome of their law.
No easie meanes according to his mind.
The Prince according to the former token,
He staide his hand according her desire,
Who being askt, accordingly confessed all.
For all the shores, which to the sea accoste,
Here to account the endlesse progenie
But that same froward twaine would accourage,
Her to recomfort, and accourage bold,
Accourting each her friend with lauish fest:
And with kind words accoyd, vowing great loue to mee.
About the Caudron many Cookes accoyld,
And though powre faild, her courage did accrew:
Hauing his forces all in one accrewed,
When those accursed messengers of hell,
Into the hands of his accursed fone,
Accursed vsurie was all his trade,
And to my selfe, and to accursed fate
But that accursed Hag, her hostesse late,
Entrenched deepe with knife accursed keene,
Of this accursed Carle of hellish kind;
Thereto they vsde one most accursed order,
To see th'vnkindly Impes of heauen accurst,
And that accurst hand-writing doth deface,
Well worthie thou to be of Ioue accurst,
And euermore the Carle of curtesie accusd.
Shall I accuse the hidden cruell fate,
His almes for want of faith he doth accuse;
But thing refused, do not afterward accuse.
With which she guiltlesse persons may accuse,
Least if men you of cruelty accuse,
The heauens of their fortunes fault accuse,
His father fierce of treason false accused,
But many there she found, which sore accused
And lewd Impietie, that her accused sore.
Vpon his steed, for no iust cause accused,
Of a rude churle, whom often he accused
And new accusements to produce in place:
And his accuser thereuppon defide:
And her accusing of dishonesty,
As heauen accusing guiltie of her death,
Accusing fortune, and too cruell fate,
Accusing highest Ioue and gods ingrate,
Such was this Ladies fit, in her loues fond accusing.
The martiall brood accustomed to fight:
As the proud Persian Queenes accustomed:
Did order all th'Achates in seemely wise,
They pas the bitter waues of Acheron,
Achilles armes, which Arthegall did win.
Therefore it rightly cleeped was mount Acidale.
On Acidalian mount, where many an howre
Her selfe acknowledg'd bound for that accord,
Acknowledg'd for his owne faire Pastorell.
With which Acontius got his louer trew,
Where shortly they in great acquaintance grew,
Ne in this new acquaintaunce could delight,
Who well acquainted with that commune plight,
But she that neuer had acquainted beene
We needes must passe (God do vs well acquight,)
For till I haue acquit your captiue knight,
Sir Terpin, from her direfull doome acquit,
Which had himselfe so stoutly well acquit;
And stedfast truth acquite him out of all.
And did acquite a murdrer felonous;
Him selfe thereof he labour'd to acquite,
And how thereof her selfe she did acquite,
I will them soone acquite, and both of blame assoile.
To come, where vile Acrasia does wonne,
Acrasia a false enchaunteresse,
Till I that false Acrasia haue wonne;
The vile Acrasia, that with vaine delightes,
For thou to serue Acrasia thy selfe doest vaunt.
Of false Acrasia, and her wicked wiles,
Here wonnes Acrasia, whom we must surprise,
But the captiu'd Acrasia he sent,
and Acrasie defeat.
The sonnes of old Acrates and Despight,
Acrates sonne of Phlegeton and Iarre;
What is become of great Acrates sonne?
Acrates sonnes despoyld,
Those were the two sonnes of Acrates old
To proue how many acres he did spread of land.
Ah heauens, that do this hideous act behold,
And liues he yet (said he) that wrought this act,
She was empassiond at that piteous act,
Whose euery act and word, that he did say,
Speedy Hippothoe, and chaste Actea,
That euery action doth them much commend,
His stedfast life, and all his actions frame,
And all their actions to direct aright;
By liuely actions he gan bewray
That liuing him in all actiuity
And th'actours won the meede meet for their crymes.
Though now their acts be no where to be found,
He would be there, and honor to her spousall ad.
Hewen out of Adamant rocke with engines keene,
As if in Adamant rocke it had bene pight.
But her in chaines of adamant he tyde;
Tempred with Adamant amongst the same,
Whose character in th'Adamantine mould
But th'Adamantine shield, which he did beare,
Proud of his Adamants, with which he shines
Enwombed was, from wretched Adams line
The sight whereof did greatly him adaw,
And haughtie spirits meekely to adaw,
And feruour of his flames somewhat adaw:
As one adaw'd, and halfe confused stood;
Like one adawed with some dreadfull spright.
Add faith vnto your force, and be not faint:
Yet now some hope your words vnto me add.
And of her plenty adde vnto their need:
And now he strength gan adde vnto his will,
My labour adde, and be partaker of their speed.
Thereto adde art, euen womens witty trade,
And thereto added words of wondrous might:
And added grace vnto her excellence:
But added flame vnto his former fire,
And that aboue were added to that vnder ground.
There added was by goodly ordinaunce,
New matter added to his former fire;
Addeem'd me to endure this penaunce sore;
So vnto him they did addeeme the prise
He, like an Adder, lurking in the weeds,
Curled with thousand adders venemous,
He answerd nought at all, but adding new
And after adding more impetuous forse,
And adding anguish to the bitter wound,
To which he adding comely guize withall,
And bad her knight addresse him to the fray:
And vnto battaill bad them selues addresse:
That streight against that knight his speare he did addresse.
And vnto battell doe your selues addresse;
And on his arme addresse his goodly shield
Sir Satyrane him towards did addresse,
And gan their shields addresse them selues afore:
Did to the Faery Queene her way addresse,
They gan themselues addresse, full rich aguiz'd,
Goe damzell quickly, doe thy selfe addresse,
Gan her addresse vnto her former way.
And gan with courage fierce addresse him to the fight.
Thereto addresse, and his bright shield display.
Gan freshly him addresse vnto his former way.
Which that nights fortune would for him addresse.
But gan himselfe addresse to take her part.
He wist not to which side him to addresse.
Eftsoones her goodly shield addressing faire,
Full iolly knight he seemde, and well addrest,
Vpon his manly arme he soone addrest,
Whom when the Prince, to battell new addrest,
And this good knight his way with me addrest,
And fresh encounter towards him addrest:
Her greeting sends in these sad lines addrest,
Vprose from drowsie couch, and him addrest
He to Cordelia him selfe addrest,
Him selfe addrest to that aduenture hard:
He to the Carle himselfe againe addrest,
Till that to the sea-coast at length she her addrest.
Is wicked Time, who with his scyth addrest,
Her selfe to fight addrest, and threw her lode aside.
Her dreadfull weapon she to him addrest,
Yet he himselfe so busily addrest,
They all agree, and forward them addrest:
To her this song most fitly is addrest,
The warlike Britonesse her soone addrest,
His foe was soone addrest: the trompets freshly blew.
Against Cambello fiercely him addrest;
Gainst whom Sir Paridell himselfe addrest,
Of knights, addrest his maiden-headed shield,
And after him Sir Douglas him addrest,
Therewith she rose in hast, and her addrest
Eftsoones him selfe he to their aide addrest,
And streight him selfe vnto the fight addrest,
Towards which coast her loue his way addrest.
His dwelling was, to which he him addrest;
And to his former iourney him addrest,
Himselfe addrest vnto this new debate,
And doffing his bright armes, himselfe addrest
Or other daintie thing for her addrest,
Adicia to despaire.
By his bad wife, that hight Adicia,
Fit for Adicia, there to build her wicked bowre.
Adieu, but nimbly ran her wonted course
Hight Adin, and the king of Orkeny,
She lightly vnto him adioyned side to syde;
Built on a rocke adioyning to the seas:
To losse of loue adioyning losse of frend,
Was next adioyning, ne them parted ought:
Out of the rockes and caues adioyning nye,
The fayrest Ladie was adiudgd for Paramore.
The honour of the prize should be adiudg'd by those.
And she her selfe adiudged to the Knight,
Tho vnto Satyran she was adiudged,
Nayld to a post, adiudged so by law:
I am adiur'd, best counsell to impart
The seruant of Admetus cowheard vile,
To haue done much more admirable deedes.
That Turrets frame most admirable was,
That seemd a worke of admirable wit;
With great admiraunce inwardly was moued,
That all the Gods admird his loftie note.
Admir'd of all the people, and much glorifide.
And oft admir'd his monstrous shape, and oft
The more it is admir'd of many a wight,
Gan her admire, and her sad sorrowes rew,
He may it find; ne let him then admire,
That mortall men her glory should admire
Whose great assembly they did much admire,
Her wisedome did admire, and hearkned to her loring.
Him much more now, then earst he gan admire,
That all men did her person much admire,
And him did oft embrace, and oft admire,
That all this worlds gay showes, which we admire,
Whom all admired, as from heauen sent,
Sir Scudamour there entring, much admired
Their like resemblaunce much admired there,
Yet was admired much of fooles, women, and boys.
He much admired both his heart and hew,
So with the Squire, th'admirer of his might,
Who her admiring as some heauenly wight,
For all so soone as life did me admit
She would admit, albe the knight her much did pray.
He as a Knight might iustly be admitted;
But Talus mote not be admitted to her part.
Admyrd her goodly haueour, and found
Admyr'd her beautie much, as she mote well:
And men admyr'd his ouerruling might;
Admyr'd of many, honoured of all,
Admyr'd of all the rest in presence there,
Tempred so well, but more admyr'd the stroke
And much admyr'd the Beast, but more admyr'd the Knight.
And much admyr'd the Beast, but more admyr'd the Knight.
That all men much admyrde her change, and spake her praise.
Much did Sir Calidore admyre his speach
But simple Truth did rayne, and was of all admyred.
He praysd it much, and much admyred it;
Which the late world admyres for wondrous monime[n]ts.
I much admyring that so goodly frame,
By which I hardly past with much adoe:
For ye haue much adoe to deale withall.
With small adoe, and nature satisfyde,
Did in the gardins of Adonis find
The faire Adonis, turned to a flowre,
The Gardins of Adonis fraught
The Gardin of Adonis, farre renowmd by fame.
That in the Gardin of Adonis springs,
Her deare Adonis ioyous company,
Aside, with faire Adonis playes his wanton parts.
And dead as liuing euer him ador'd:
Her that him lou'd, and euer most adord,
And her ador'd by honorable name,
Which her ador'd, may sore repent with me,
And doubly ouercommen, her ador'd:
Iustice sate high ador'd with solemne feasts,
That would compell all nations to adore,
Whom saluage nation does adore,
Whom highly he did reuerence and adore,
Do her adore with sacred reuerence,
And his deare hart the picture gan adore,
Dying her serue, and liuing her adore;
And thought her to adore with humble spright;
Yet tried did adore. Supper was dight;
Both for his worth, that all men did adore,
All other Idoles, which the heathen adore
Congealed litle drops, which doe the morne adore.
Much did that Squire Sir Artegall adore,
